        <h2 class="text-center">Fueling for Exercise</h2>
        <br>
        <p style="font-size:18px" class="text-justify">Proper nutrition is important for fueling your body for exercise and helping you recover afterwards. Eating a balanced diet with plenty of fruits, vegetables, lean proteins, whole grains, and healthy fats can help you perform at your best.</p>
      </div>

      <div id="timingOfMealsSection" >   
      <br>   
      <br>   
      <br> 
        <h2 class="text-center">Timing of Meals</h2>
        <br>
      
      <div class="container">
      <div class="row">  
      <div class="col-sm">
      <br>

        <p style="font-size:18px" class="text-justify">The timing of your meals can also play a role in your exercise performance. Eating a meal or snack containing carbohydrates and protein about 2-3 hours before exercise can help provide your body with the energy it needs to perform. If you are exercising within an hour or less, a small snack such as a piece of fruit or a granola bar may be sufficient.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="col-sm text-center">
        <img src="https://st3.depositphotos.com/6760872/19294/v/600/depositphotos_192942352-stock-illustration-white-plate-with-clock-fork.jpg" alt="Runner" width="250" height="250" class="rounded mx-auto d-block">
      </div>
      </div>
      </div> 

      </div>  

      <div id="hydrationSection" > 
            <br>   
      <br>   
      <br>    
        <h2 class="text-center">Hydration</h2>
        <br>
       
      <div class="container">
      <div class="row">  
      <div class="col-sm text-center">
        <img src="https://t4.ftcdn.net/jpg/02/17/80/87/360_F_217808785_L35Xg436j0hOW1CNCAvtGa6I7e4OKSNW.jpg" alt="Runner" width="300" height="200" class="d-flex align-items-center rounded mx-auto d-block">
      </div>
      <div class="col-sm">
      <br>
        <p style="font-size:18px" class="text-justify d-flex align-items-center">Staying hydrated is crucial for exercise performance and recovery. Drink water before, during, and after exercise to replenish fluids lost through sweat. The amount of water you need will vary depending on factors such as the intensity and duration of your workout, as well as the temperature and humidity of your environment.</p>
      </div>
      </div>
      </div> 

      </div>
      
      <div id="macronutrientsSection" > 
            <br>   
      <br>   
      <br> 
        <h2 class="text-center">Macronutrients</h2>
        <br> 
      <div class="container">
      <div class="row">  
      <div class="col-sm">
      <br>
        <p style="font-size:18px" class="text-justify d-flex align-items-center">The three macronutrients are carbohydrates, proteins, and fats, and all play important roles in exercise performance and recovery. Carbohydrates are the primary source of energy for exercise, while protein helps repair and build muscle tissue. Healthy fats can also provide energy and help with hormone production.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="col-sm text-center">
        <img src="https://img.freepik.com/premium-vector/macronutrients-diagram-with-food-ingredients_1639-48440.jpg?w=2000" alt="Runner" width="480" height="200" class="d-flex align-items-center rounded mx-auto d-block">
      </div>
      </div>
      </div> 

      </div> 

